{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531183"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14583"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14583"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.01,0.2,0.75,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7276"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7276"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42593"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"185"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2647"},{"type":"tags","id":"2775"},{"type":"tags","id":"2971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4856"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17771"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of progressive fatigue, tingling in her hands and feet, and difficulty maintaining balance. She reports feeling increasingly forgetful and confused. She has a medical history of autoimmune hypothyroidism and osteoarthritis. Her medications include thyroxine and paracetamol. She lives alone and maintains an adequate diet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals reduced vibration sense and proprioception in both feet, with diminished ankle reflexes. She has difficulty with heel-to-toe walking. Mini-Mental State Examination score is 24/30. Her tongue appears smooth and red.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests show haemoglobin 98 g/L (115-165), mean cell volume 102 fL (80-96), vitamin B12 85 pmol/L (150-700), vitamin D 40 nmol/L (50-150), and positive intrinsic factor antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Folic acid supplementation","Dietary modification","Oral vitamin B12 1000 micrograms daily","Intramuscular vitamin B12 1000 micrograms three times per week","Vitamin D supplementation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of vitamin B12 deficiency including macrocytic anaemia, peripheral neuropathy, cognitive decline, and glossitis. The presence of intrinsic factor antibodies confirms pernicious anaemia as the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular vitamin B12\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment as it bypasses the need for intrinsic factor-mediated absorption. The loading regimen typically involves 1000 micrograms three times per week for two weeks, followed by maintenance therapy of 1000 micrograms every three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral vitamin B12\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be ineffective in this case due to the lack of intrinsic factor, which is necessary for B12 absorption in the terminal ileum. While high-dose oral therapy can achieve some passive absorption, the presence of neurological symptoms warrants more reliable parenteral therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDietary modification\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient to correct B12 deficiency in pernicious anaemia, as the underlying problem is absorption rather than intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFolic acid\u003C/strong\u003E supplementation without B12 replacement could potentially mask the haematological manifestations of B12 deficiency while allowing neurological damage to progress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D\u003C/strong\u003E supplementation, while indicated given the low level, is not the priority in this case. The neurological symptoms and anaemia are more urgent clinical issues requiring immediate attention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular monitoring of the patient\u0027s haematological and neurological response to treatment is essential. While the anaemia typically improves within weeks, neurological symptoms may take months to resolve, and some deficits may be permanent if treatment is delayed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Vitamin B12 deficiency commonly presents with macrocytic anaemia, peripheral neuropathy, and cognitive changes in elderly patients.","Intramuscular B12 replacement is preferred over oral therapy in pernicious anaemia due to impaired intrinsic factor production.","Regular monitoring of haematological response and neurological symptoms is essential in B12 deficiency treatment."],"references":["Gad\u00f3 K, Khodier M, Vir\u00e1g A, Domj\u00e1n G, D\u00f6rnyei G. Anemia of geriatric patients. Physiology international. 2022 Jun 7. Available online at ; https://akjournals.com/view/journals/2060/109/2/article-p119.xml","Mouchaileh N. Vitamin B12 deficiency in older people: a practical approach to recognition and management. Journal of Pharmacy Practice and Research. 2023 Dec;53(6):350-8. Available online at ; https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/jppr.1897"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42593"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14583"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42593"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T18:28:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T18:29:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7276"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57134"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":nu